OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-19, and the batch number was 1800146.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Pesticides in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using Modified EPA 8321A
LaboratoryName: U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Region 8 Laboratory, CO

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-19, and the batch number was 1800145.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Pesticides in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using Modified EPA 8321A
LaboratoryName: U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Region 8 Laboratory, CO

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Approximate value result is below the reporting level but greater than the method detection limit

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-19, and the batch number was 1800169.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC PPCPs in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using EPA 1694, Positive Mode

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 NO3 F ~ Nitrate in Water- Automated Cadmium Reduction

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-15, and the batch number was 1800169.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC PPCPs in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using EPA 1694, Positive Mode

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Approximate value result is below the reporting level but greater than the method detection limit

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.

ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC PPCPs in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using EPA 1694, Negative Mode

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 5310 B ~ Total Organic Carbon by Combustion-Infrared Method

Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-15, and the batch number was 1800145.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Pesticides in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using Modified EPA 8321A

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-15, and the batch number was 1800146.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Pesticides in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using Modified EPA 8321A
LaboratoryName: U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Region 8 Laboratory, CO

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.

ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-19, and the batch number was 1800169.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC PPCPs in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using EPA 1694, Positive Mode

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-15, and the batch number was 1800146.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

ProjectName: GLAC Lake McDonald Water Quality Study, 2018
MonitoringLocationName: Lake McDonald near Lake McDonald Lodge, North Site
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC Sampling for Pesticides, PPCPs & Waste Indicators
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection.  National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program; 2017; Quality Assurance Project Plan for Surface Water Sampling for Pesticides, Pharmaceuticals, Personal Care Products in the National Park Service's Northern Colorado Plateau, Southern Colorado Plateau, Sierra Nevada, Great Lakes, Heartland, Sonoran Desert, and Southern Plains Inventory and Monitoring Networks: Describing Operations for the Year 2017; National Park Service - Water Resources Division and Inventory & Monitoring Program, Fort Collins, CO; 89 pp.
ResultCommentText: The lab number was 1807007-19, and the batch number was 1800169.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: EPA/NPS-EC PPCPs in Water by Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry Using EPA 1694, Positive Mode

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: A summary for collecting a subsurface water sample used by the EPA/NPS Emerging Contaminants program is as follows. Contact the laboratory before sampling to notify the lab when samples will arrive. At the sampling site, lower an amber glass container to the desired depth (at least 18 inches if possible) with the lid on. Remove the lid under water. Rinse the container two times with sample water and then sample from a similar depth as above. Fill the container completely. Avoid collecting disturbed sediment. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Prepare or collect duplicate samples as necessary for quality control. After collection all samples will be immediately placed in a cooler with wet or Blue ice and kept cool until delivered to the laboratory. If samples must be stored temporarily, they should be refrigerated at 4.5º C or lower to prevent microbial degradation. Samples will be shipped via UPS overnight service to the laboratory. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. Replace the lid and lift the container out of the water. Dry the container thoroughly and label with project name, sample ID, sample date, sampled by, sample time, preservative (ice), grab sample, and analysis requested (pest/PPCP, waste). Repeat the above procedure until the appropriate number of samples have been collected. Use new or clean gloves when collecting each additional sample. Samples should be shipped to the laboratory as soon as possible after collection and should be received by the laboratory 7 or less days after the time of collection. OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Lab reported a result value, but lab's detection limit not known/available for comparison to the result; however with parameter specific evaluation determined to be quantified.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Lab reported a result value, but lab's detection limit not known/available for comparison to the result; however with parameter specific evaluation determined to be quantified.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: Alkalinity by Gran Titration

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Lachat QuikChem 8500 Series 2 Flow Injection Analyzer
LaboratoryName: Kiowa Labs

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Metrohm 761 Compact Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Kiowa Labs

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the method detection limit (MDL) and entered at the MDL. Reporting limit not known.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 200.7 W  ~ Metals in Water by ICP-AES
LaboratoryName: U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Region 8 Laboratory

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Shimadzu TOC-V CSN

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the reporting limit (PQL or LQL) and entered at the PQL. True method detection limit not known.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 200.7 W  ~ Metals in Water by ICP-AES

Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Reported value was at or below the reporting limit (PQL or LQL) and entered at the PQL. True method detection limit not known.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 200.7 W  ~ Metals in Water by ICP-AES

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Perkin Elmer AAnalyst 200 Atomic Absorption Spectrometer
LaboratoryName: Kiowa Labs

Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Shimadzu TOC-V CSN
LaboratoryName: Kiowa Labs

Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Metrohm 761 Compact Ion Chromatography
LaboratoryName: Kiowa Labs

Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Shimadzu TOC-V CSN

Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Shimadzu TOC-V CSN
LaboratoryName: Kiowa Labs

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Lab reported a result value, but lab's detection limit not known/available for comparison to the result; however with parameter specific evaluation determined to be quantified.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Lachat QuikChem 8500 Series 2 Flow Injection Analyzer

SampleCollectionMethod/MethodName: Rocky Mountain Network Grab Sample Procedure
SampleCollectionMethod/MethodDescription: Water and sediment samples are collected at the downstream end of the sample reach using modified USGS/NPS procedures. All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Unspecified Nitrogen Method

Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: CU's Kiowa Lab's Lachat QuikChem 8500 Series 2 Flow Injection Analyzer

All bottles are triple rinsed with stream water prior to filling. All crew wear nitrile gloves. Water is collected in the thalweg with a isokinetic technique with bottles filled facing upstream and plunged in a smooth even motion from the surface to the bottom substrate. Filtration is conducted on site or within 24 hours as needed. Fine mineral sediment is composited from 7 to 11 representative areas near the location where water is sampled. Samples are preserved and frozen or refrigerated within 24 hours as needed.
ResultCommentText: Approximate value result is below the reporting level but greater than the method detection limit
ResultAnalyticalMethod/MethodName: 4500 NO3 F ~ Nitrate in Water- Automated Cadmium Reduction
LaboratoryName: Oregon State University Cooperative Chemical Analytical Labo
